dependent.value:
Participants will repeat pseudo-random presentations of the target words “cat”, “sat” and “pat” with their lower jaw physically coupled to a 3D-position robotic device by means of a custom-made dental appliance. After a baseline period of 45 trials (15 per word), a velocity-dependent force-field will be applied by the robot during each utterance. Force magnitude will be proportional to jaw velocity along the primary axis of jaw opening (extracted using PCA analysis of a speech sample in pretest) with a target peak of 4N at peak velocity (force-field gain necessary to achieve this also extracted during pre-test procedure). The force will be applied along the secondary axis of jaw opening (also extracted from pretest PCA) such that it will act to protrude the jaw outwards orthogonally to the opening trajectory. The force-field will remain on for 105 trials (35 per word) before it is suddenly removed again for a final washout block of 45 trials (15 per word) when the task will finish. In each trial (except for the first 9 [3 per word] which will be discarded to eliminate familiarization effects), jaw kinematics will be assessed by calculating the maximal deviation of jaw position along the secondary axis relative to the averaged trajectory during baseline trials (hereafter “jaw deviation from baseline”). 

DV 1 – Adaptation Extent;
We will use two separate measures of adaptation extent. First, we will determine the jaw deviation from baseline averaged across trials at the end of the perturbation block. Second, the trial by trial jaw deviation data during the perturbation block will be fitted with a function (to be determined based on a best-fit comparison) and then the value of the fit at the last trial will also provide an index of adaptation extent. 

DV 2 – Adaptation Rate;
We will also use two measures of adaptation rate. First, we will determine for each subject the epoch number where 25%, 50%, and 75% of the individual’s final extent of adaptation was reached on the fitted function. This will allow the rate of learning to be compared between groups for three different time scales (i.e., not limited to only the initial rate). Second, we will use the rate parameter of the fitted function to determine of overall rate of adaptation.

DV 3 – After-effects;
Persistent effects of the speech motor adaptation (after the perturbation is suddenly removed) will be measured as average jaw deviation from baseline across early trials in the washout block.

